\chapter{Contexte historique et géographique}

\begin{figure}[hbt!]
  \includegraphics[width=1.0\textwidth]{forts_ramses}%
  \caption{Les fortifications de Marmarique}
\end{figure}

% \begin{multicols}{2}

\begin{comment}
The whole area to the west of the Nile valley and the Delta except 
from the Oases is referred to as by the egyptologists as Libya, and 
the people there as Libyans. Two major groups of Libyans were known to 
the Egyptians in the period from the beginning of Egyptian history to 
the late 18th dynasty: the Tchemay and the Tjehenou. These appear to 
be semi-nomad people who moved over a wide territory with perhaps a 
concentration of occupation on the fertile Mediterranean coast.
\end{comment}

Toute la région à l'ouest de la vallée du Nil \incise{à l'exception 
des oasis} est appelée \emph{Libye} et sa population \emph{Libyens} 
par les égyptologues.

Du début de l'histoire égyptienne jusqu'à la \dyn{xviii}, les 
égyptiens connaissaient deux principaux groupes de libyens : les 
\emph{Tjéméhous} et les \emph{Tjéhénous}, des semi-nomades occupant 
un vaste territoire avec peut-être une concentration plus importante 
sur la côte fertile de la Méditerranée.

\begin{comment}
However, to an Egyptian soldier or an administrator who lived during 
the 18th dynasty \incise{the period of Egypt's greatest imperial 
power} the area to the west of Egypt would have seem to be the least 
significant of Egypt immediate neighbours. It is an area which did 
not attract (to) Egypt because it did not offer any opportunities for 
economic exploitation. But nor did it offer any threat to the security 
of Egypt itself. As an area which had neither opportunity nor threat, 
unlike both of Levant and Nubia which historically had provided plenty 
of both, Libya was therefore of little interest. It was certainly 
unworthy of expensive investment in the form of military conquest 
or the creation of a colonial infrastructure of administration. 
This situation changed drastically in the period from the reign of 
Amenhotep III to that of Ramesses II. In that period, Egypt came into 
contact with new Libyan groups, especially the Meshwesh and the Libu. 
The origin of these groups is not certain. Perhaps Cyrenaica. But we 
do know that these groups were real threat to Egypt itself. Their 
attempted migration into Egypt resulted in major defensive wars under 
Ramesses II's successor Merenptah and a little later under Ramesses 
III when the survival of the Egyptian state itself was in danger. 
The threat had been recognised during the reign of Ramesses II's 
father Sethy I and under Ramesses II himself when a new series of 
fortifications were built for western Delta (desert towns) including 
Tell el-...yn, ... and Kom el-.... An extension of this west Delta 
system was the creation of a system of forts or fortress towns along 
that part of the Mediterranean coast which is referred to as 
Marmarica.
\end{comment}

Jusqu'à la \dyn{xviii}, l'\kmt se désintéresse de cette région qui ne 
présente \incise{contrairement à la Nubie et au Levant} ni opportunité 
économique ni danger.
La situation change cependant radicalement entre les règnes 
d'Amenhotep~III et celui de Ramsès~II, quand l'\kmt entre en contact 
avec de nouveaux groupes de Libyens, particulièrement les 
\emph{Mechouech} et les \emph{Libous}, qui pourraient être originaires 
de Cyrénaïque. Ce que l'on sait, c'est que ces groupes représentaient 
un réel danger et que leur tentative de migration en \kmt a résulté en 
d'importantes guerres défensives sous Mérenptah et plus tard sous 
Ramsès~III. Ce danger, identifié déjà sous Séthi~I\ier et Ramsès~II, 
est à l'origine de la mise en place d'un réseau de fortifications dans 
le Delta occidental (notamment Tell el-Abqa'in et Kôm el-Hisn), 
prolongé par un système de villes fortifiées le long le la côte 
méditerranéenne de la Marmarique.

