\chapter{L'entrée nord}

% \begin{multicols}{2}

\begin{comment}
The first area I would like to direct attention is the main gate of 
the fortress. I said ``main gate'', it was the only. It was located 
in the middle of the northern wall, composed of two now denuded 
towers of mud brick, originally with some external limestone cladding 
and with a central corridor wide and floored with substantial slabs 
of limestone. Although badly damaged and surviving (less than) 1.5m 
of ... the outer \incise{that's to say northern faces of this gate} 
contain inscriptions which seem to indicate at least part of the 
agenda for this fortress town. A fragmentary text refers to (menen) 
fortresses on the hill country of the Tchemay. This is important for 
several reasons. A (menen) fortress is a large fortress town, not a 
small simple fort, a description which seems an excellent description 
of ZUeR. It is also (noteworthy) that the inscription refers to 
(menen) fortresses in the plural, which suggests other similar 
fortress towns along the Marmarican coast. A second set of interesting 
texts is to be found on door jams and door lintels from the area of 
the main gate. These contain short texts which refer to Ramesses II 
crushing foreign enemies. However, it should be noted that on the door 
jams which have been recovered to date, and record this activity, only 
Libyan groups are recorded, especially the Tchemay, the Tjehenou, and 
the Libu.
\end{comment}

La première zone d'intérêt est celle de l'unique entrée 
(\fref{fig:entree} et~\ref{fig:entreedet}), située au milieu du mur 
nord et composé de deux (\frquote{denuded} ?) tours de briques crues 
et à l'origine dotées d'un parement en calcaire.

Le large corridor central est pavé de grandes dalles de calcaire. 
Bien qu'en mauvais état, et avec seulement \SI{1.5}{\m} d'élévation 
conservée, la face externe de cette entrée comporte des inscriptions 
qui semblent révéler au moins en partie la raison d'être de la 
forteresse. Un texte fragmentaire fait référence à des forteresses 
\emph{\frquote{menen}} dans les collines du pays des Tjéméhous.

\CaptionPetit
\begin{wrapfigure}[25]{l}[0.0cm]{0pt}
  \includegraphics[width=7cm]{ZURentree}
  \caption{L'entrée nord, détail}
  \label{fig:entreedet}
\end{wrapfigure}
\CaptionNormal

Ce terme désigne non pas un simple fort, mais une ville fortifiée de 
bonne taille, ce qui semble tout à fait correspondre à \ZOR. On peut 
également noter que le terme est employé au pluriel, ce qui suggère 
d'autres villes fortifiées le long de la côte de la Marmarique. Une 
autre série de textes intéressants se trouve sur les jambages et 
linteaux et mentionne Ramsès~II écrasant des ennemis étrangers (les 
éléments mis au jour jusque là ne citent que des groupes libyens, 
Tjéméhous, Tjéhénous et Libous).

% \end{multicols}


\chapter{Temple et chapelles}

% \begin{multicols}{2}

\begin{comment}
On the western side of the fortress, ... excavated a temple which we 
later re-excavated in order to record it. This temple is constructed 
of substantial slabs of limestone and its architectural form is 
comparable to some contemporary ramesside temples in both Nubia and 
in Egypt itself, although not of course Abu Simbel. The poor quality 
limestone has not survived very well though the temple has a number of 
interesting features such as this 13'03 paved procesionnal route and 
courtyard with a bark stand. Temple : no inscriptions, no idea which 
god(s) is (are) worshiped there
\end{comment}


Un temple (\fref{fig:temple}) est situé à l'ouest du site, construit 
en larges dalles de calcaire et dont la forme architecturale est 
comparable à celle de temples ramessides contemporains en \kmt et 
Nubie\footnote{Pas Abou Simbel, \emph{of course} !}. Le calcaire de 
mauvaise qualité à très mal résisté, mais le temple présente des 
éléments intéressants, parmi lesquels une voie processionnelle pavée 
et une cour avec un support de barque.
Aucune inscription ne permet de savoir à quelle(s) divinité(s) il 
était dédié.

\begin{comment}
A group of three small chapels was located ... in the south (?) of 
the temple. Limestone stelae found here suggest that they were used 
for private worship by military officers based in ZUeR. The stelea 
are useful in other ways. It is only difficult to estimate the number 
of people who lived in ancient settlements. However one useful piece 
of information which can help us is this stela excavated in ZUeR near
the temple. Although it is in very poor condition we can identify two 
officers, each with the title "standard bearer". In the NK, this 
title identify the commander of a company which in the Ramesside army 
consisted of between 200 and 250 men. Because two standard bearers 
are shown together on the stelea it is reasonable to assume that they 
serve as officers at ZUeR at the same time. And therefore at least two 
companies were present at ZUeR at one time, making a minimum garrison 
of 400 to 500 men.
\end{comment}

Au sud du temple, on trouve un groupe de trois chapelles utilisées 
comme lieu de culte privé par des officiers en garnison, comme le 
suggèrent les stèles qui y ont été découvertes.
Sur l'une d'elles, malgré son mauvais état de conservation, on peut 
identifier deux officiers portant chacun le titre de 
\frquote{porte-enseigne} (\tl{TAy sry.t} en égyptien). Au \NK, ce 
titre est porté par les commandants de compagnie, des groupes de deux 
cents à deux cent cinquante hommes dans les armées ramessides. La 
présence de ces deux personnages sur une même stèle permet de supposer 
qu'ils ont servi en même temps en tant qu'officiers à \ZOR. On peut 
donc estimer à un minimum de quatre cents à cinq cents hommes la 
garnison de la ville à un moment donné.

% \end{multicols}


\chapter{Comptoir commercial}

% \begin{multicols}{2}

\begin{comment}
A row of nine stoves (?) with entrances facing east fill the space 
between the temple and the northern wall of the fortress. One of 
theses produced the first examples of imported non Egyptian pottery 
in ZUeR. We have since found significant quantities of such pottery 
including large transport and storage vessels such as these large 
coarse ... stone (?) jars probably from Greece or Crete or Cyprus and 
... from somewhere along the Levantine coast. These were used for the 
movement of goods such as olive oil or wine. Small imports include 
flasks which are Cypriots or Mycenaean in origin. It is very likely 
that all of this foreign pottery arrived by sea from some ... as part 
of the great East Mediterranean maritime trading circuit. This trade 
route which ran around the coast of the east of the Mediterranean was 
vital for trading links between Egypt, the Hittite Empire, trading 
cities of the Levant such as Byblos and Ras Shamra, Mycenae, Greece 
and Crete. The wide range of origins for the vessels found in ZUeR 
from almost all the significant trading regions of the late Bronze Age 
eastern Mediterranean ... ZUeR role as a point on the route around the 
eastern Mediterranean. It is likely that these material found their 
way at ZUeR as a form of unofficial customs duty by Mediterranean 
traders heading from Crete to Egypt refitting or restocking their 
ships with supplies after a long sea crossing before heading eastwards 
to Egypt.

Canaanite amphorae, Aegean coarse-ware stirrup-jars and Cypriot 
base-ring juglets
\end{comment}


Une rangée de neuf magasins dont les entrées font face à l'est 
remplit l'espace entre le temple et le mur nord. La zone a fournit de
grande quantité de poterie d'importation, destinées au transport et au 
stockage de denrées telles que l'huile d'olive ou le vin par exemple. 
On peut citer des jarres en pierre provenant probablement de Grèce, 
Crète ou Chypre, ou d'autres récipients~\dots originaires de la côte 
levantine, et, parmi les pièces de petite taille, des flasques 
chypriotes ou mycéniennes. Il est très probable que ces importations 
soient arrivées là par le biais des routes commerciales maritimes de 
la Méditerranée orientale. Ces routes qui desservent toute la côte 
orientale de la Méditerranée étaient un lien vital pour le commerce 
entre l'\kmt, l'empire Hittite, les cités du Levant (Byblos, Ras 
Shamra), Mycènes, la Grèce et la Crète et \ZOR en était manifestement 
une étape.
Il est également probable que ces biens correspondent à des droits de 
douane non-officiels dont s'acquittaient les marchands voyageant de 
Crète jusqu'en \kmt et profitant d'une étape pour retaper leurs 
bateaux et se réapprovisionner avant de poursuivre vers l'est et \kmt.

\begin{comment}
The importance of this foreign trade suggests a possible reason for 
the existence of ZUeR. It seems to me that the main function of ZUeR 
was not primarily to act as a shield against ... invasions from 
Syrenaica because ... a large garrison in a world defending fortress 
could not stop such a massive population movement although it could 
delay its progress. But equally it is so big that you cannot simply 
be part of an early warning system for such an invasion.
I believe ZUeR and possibly other fortresses was built to maintain a 
considerable ... in order to protect this part of the north African 
coast as a secure and vital element of this east Mediterranean trade 
system. 
It is likely that the perceived threat to the integrity of this 
circuit was the group of new Lybians with their ... increased level of 
activity in Marmarica, operating to the east of their probable 
homeland in syreanica. It may well be that these new Lybian groups 
were threatened rather than participant in this Mediterranean circuit 
in a way which was not the case with old Chamay, Tjemenu groups. The 
appearance of an Egyptian presence in the region where non existed 
earlier should probably be seen in the context of the need to protect 
the status quo, that's to say an ... access ... mariners as a response 
to this new and emergent threat.
\end{comment}

